1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:18,320
Walsh, those things that go from the floor of the ceiling in physical security, we're

2
00:00:18,320 --> 00:00:19,840
concerned with them.

3
00:00:19,840 --> 00:00:43,040
We want to know what they're made out of.

4
00:00:43,040 --> 00:00:46,160
The wall construction, in other words, what the wall is made out of, makes a big difference

5
00:00:46,160 --> 00:00:48,080
as to how secure the wall is.

6
00:00:48,080 --> 00:00:51,680
If you want a nice secure bank vault or a data center, you're probably not going to build

7
00:00:51,680 --> 00:00:56,160
your wall at a regular stick and timber, stick and frame, you're going to build it out

8
00:00:56,160 --> 00:01:00,160
of a secure concrete reinforced wall or something like that.

9
00:01:00,160 --> 00:01:03,960
A question that often comes up on the exam that you should understand is that you want

10
00:01:03,960 --> 00:01:07,840
the wall to go all the way to the real ceiling and all the way to the real floor.

11
00:01:07,840 --> 00:01:08,920
What do we mean by that?

12
00:01:08,920 --> 00:01:12,640
Well, in a lot of office buildings, it's very common to have what's called a false ceiling.

13
00:01:12,640 --> 00:01:15,880
If you look up in your office, you'll probably see something just like this.

14
00:01:15,880 --> 00:01:17,280
We've got these looks like panels.

15
00:01:17,280 --> 00:01:21,240
You can push those panels out and you'll find that there's another 2, 3, 4 feet of

16
00:01:21,240 --> 00:01:27,680
space between that drop ceiling and the actual real ceiling of the concrete floor above.

17
00:01:27,680 --> 00:01:32,840
What you usually find up there is electrical wiring and HVAC piping and things like that.

18
00:01:32,840 --> 00:01:37,200
The reason I'm mentioning this is that in a lot of office spaces, if you push up one

19
00:01:37,200 --> 00:01:40,720
of those ceiling panels and you look over, if there's a wall in front of you and you push

20
00:01:40,720 --> 00:01:45,800
up the ceiling panel, you can often see over into the next space because the wall doesn't

21
00:01:45,800 --> 00:01:50,640
truly go to the actual ceiling, it just goes up to the drop ceiling.

22
00:01:50,640 --> 00:01:54,600
If you want a good, secure area, if you have a higher valley area that you want to protect

23
00:01:54,600 --> 00:01:58,440
access to, you've got to make sure that that wall actually truly extends all the way to

24
00:01:58,440 --> 00:02:00,040
the true ceiling.

25
00:02:00,040 --> 00:02:04,600
Within data centers, we very commonly have raised floors.

26
00:02:04,600 --> 00:02:10,440
These floors will be 24, 36 inches off the ground, off of the true floor.

27
00:02:10,440 --> 00:02:11,440
What's running underneath there?

28
00:02:11,440 --> 00:02:14,960
You've got all your electrical cables and that's usually where you duct your cold air

29
00:02:15,040 --> 00:02:16,680
for cooling the servers.

30
00:02:16,680 --> 00:02:21,920
Again, if your floor only goes to the raised floor, someone could climb underneath and get

31
00:02:21,920 --> 00:02:22,920
around.

32
00:02:22,920 --> 00:02:28,760
You've got to make sure those walls go to the true ceiling and the true floor.

33
00:02:28,760 --> 00:02:33,880
As part of this, we can monitor to see who's moving through a building.

34
00:02:33,880 --> 00:02:37,360
This is the idea of intrusion detection systems within a building.

35
00:02:37,360 --> 00:02:41,200
This is things like having motion detection sensors, having proper walls in place to

36
00:02:41,200 --> 00:02:45,160
control access and thinking about things like ventilation shafts and so forth.

37
00:02:45,160 --> 00:02:48,200
That's all part of intrusion detection within a building.

